text:
leo a much@s  muy interesados en ayudar y proteger a las mujeres de la creciente ola de #feminicidios y violencia que hay en nuestro país. 
me encanta la idea de saberlos preocupados y ocupados en ello por eso y para sumar, acá les dejo una lista de cosas con las que también nos pueden “cuidar": *dejar de llamarnos putas, zorras, perras, etc (no importa el motivo).
*dejar de sexualizar a las mujeres y/o solo reconocerlas por sus atributos físicos.
*no solapar o celebrar las actitudes y comentarios machistas de sus amig@s. *dejar de ver porno sobretodo ese que es sobre violaciones, bdsm, humillaciones y abusos. *dejar de pagar por sexo #sinclientenohaytrata
*no emborrachar o permitir que emborrachen a las amigas para que “aflojen”.
*dejar de rolar los packs de mujeres en whatsapp.
*dejar de culpar a las victimas por haber salido tarde, ir solas o vestirse de una u otra forma. 
en #méxico matan a 9 mujeres al día en y cada 6 de 10 han sufrido algún tipo de violencia (fuente: onu) y eso solo cambiará con #acciones de verdad,necesitamos cuestionar y cambiar nuestras actitudes violentas pues son las que cuando escalan terminan con nuestras vidas!

text:
the first time i encountered the word,
sexual harrassment
it was 2011
and it came on the front page,
everyday for a week,
until it didn't. 
i did not know what it meant,
so i kept reading and not knowing,
why these seemingly good men,
keenan and rueben
keenan and rueben
were killed.
every screen was ignited by the same interview,
every channel raised the same questions,
but my mother flipped through all of them,
to find other news,
easier to digest,
news i wouldn't ask questions to.
the elephant in the room,
remained the elephant in the room,
the candles in all the marches,
guttered to molten wax nothings,
the story faded from page one to four to eleven
the victims turned cold in their graves,
it took me too long too learn, why. 
the first time i heard the word rape,
in delhi,
in 2012
i did not want to know how much a body can take before it gives up,
how the city will collect 
to mourn and shriek and rage,
and in another part of the same city,
the same story will repeat itself,
over and over again,
until it sounds like a burglary or a conspiracy,
just another news item;
for the first time i did not want to grow up
to be a girl.
when you heard the word,
child sexual abuse
i really hope
it didn't feel like putting the last piece in the jigsaw,
like naming what was done on the bus,
when you were seven,
and absolving yourself of all guilt,
but not quite. 
sometimes it feels like,
the highest form of female bonding is talking about assault,
like it's not even about #metoo but more like me when,
me when i was four
me when i worked at the brothel 
me when i was in coma
me when i was on my honeymoon
me but so many times that it isn't a problem but a pattern,
this magnitude keeps escalating,
the numbers aren't numbing
but normalising,
collecting in crime against women sections in papers,
and this is not too say,
all of you are predators,
but just too many are,
just enough for our mothers to tuck
'be safe' in our hair when we step out,
just enough for outrage to be bent into acceptance
i wonder what it must be to walk alone, 
without feeling your heartbeat in your throat,
i wonder what it must be,
to walk
without knowing 
all the ways i'd have to run.

text:
طوسی رنگی محبوب برای اتاق نشیمن است و این رنگ نشان می‌دهد که شما چقدر به این اتاق علاقه داشته و عشق می‌ورزید. در عین حال این رنگ بسیار شیک و آرامش بخش است. ترکیب رنگ طوسی با بیشتر رنگ‌ها مناسب به نظر می­‌رسد و به همین دلیل نیز از طوسی به عنوان یک رنگ مناسب اتاق نشیمن یاد می‌شود. در تصویر بالا دیوارهای طوسی، موجب برجسته سازی کوسن‌های  و صورتی و درب و قاب پنجره سفید استخوانی شده است.

text:
what if people talked about your daughter the way they talked about adam levine last night?

seriously.

my social media feed is currently full of women lusting over adam levine, and frankly i’m disappointed.

it seems that there is a gross double standard in regards to what is considered appropriate to say about men vs. women. didn’t our sisters just start making headway in the #metoo movement? didn’t we tell the men in our lives that #timesup?

and yet, last night i saw women making overtly sexual and objectifying statements about adam levine.

is it because he’s a man that we feel it’s “not as bad”? is it because he took his shirt off that “he must have wanted it”? please, sisters, tell me how and why this double standard exists.

so again i ask - what if people were talking about your daughter the way they are talking about adam levine right now?

personally, i’d be so disgusted and distraught that my mama bear instinct would help me annihilate any and everyone who was saying it.

ladies, if we expect men to respect us, if we expect our sexuality to be valued and and protected, if we do not want to be objectified or have the same done to our daughters, then it’s time for us to be the change.

text:
why is being emotional used as a derogatory term?

particularly towards women.

being in tune with your emotions and, importantly, the emotions of others is a valuable life skill! us humans have learnt pretty well to try to hide certain emotions, for fear of criticism, judgement and potentially being seen as weak.

but it’s proven we feel more connected to people when we see their vulnerabilities. we trust people more when they are willing to show us their truth. so whilst there is a time and place for sharing our emotions, it’s hugely important in building both social and working relationships.

and guess what... just so happens women are better at it. so let’s stop acting like it’s a female weakness.

text_retweet:
@love.beu thank you for saying what we all needed & need to hear, many times over! 💛

#repost ・・・
i had an amazing day yesterday in london speaking with a wonderful group of ladies @tfc_thefemaleclub all about the female body and our relationship with it.
⭐️
one of the ladies pointed out how she felt so much judgement of our body’s comes from other women rather than men. i have to admit, this has been my experience too, whether it’s been ‘well meaning’ comments, subtle judgement or full on body shaming in women’s magazines. whether the articles are written by men or women, invariably they’re about a women’s body and those articles are bought and read by women.
⭐️
i offered my perspective on this, rather than it being about her, actually what she was experiencing was the other woman’s projection of her own insecurity, of her own body shame, of the judgement of her own body.
⭐️
this really highlights something essential to know, especially in today’s #metoo , patriarchy and toxic masculinity era. are we as women spreading our own pain and unhealed relationship with our body’s over every other woman in our lives? are we as women perpetuating the disempowerment of the feminine by keeping this cultural obsession with thinness alive, daily?
⭐️
taking your power back means realising it’s yours already. nobody is going to give it to you. you just have to take it. one of the most powerful ways we as women can do this today is look through kinder eyes, at our own body and of other women’s body. to take responsibility for our own healing journey and not project on to other women, onto our daughters. to hold ourself within love and know the light that we each are.
⭐️
in my book #yourbeutifulbody i ask you to make a beutiful promise, to never judge or criticise your body, or anyone else’s again. powerful. revolutionary. truly transformation, when we commit to this🙏🏻💞
.
#beu #bodypositive #foodforthought #bodyimage #projection #bodyshaming #diet #weightloss #weight #womensbodies #womenempowerment #womenshealth #nutrition #selflove #loveyourbody #bodyappreciation #bodygoals #eatingdisorderrecovery #bodyappreciation #goddess #divinefeminine #empowerment #feminism #beauty

text:
heute hatte ich eine anwaltskanzlei zu besuch im studio für businessfotos.  nach 5 minuten, als ich die krawatten aller kollegen für das gruppenfoto richtete, meinte der chef vor seinen 4 kollegen sagen zu müssen: "na los schätzchen mach schon!" zum glück hatte ich in meiner 15jährigen karriere als fotografin bisher nur 2 kunden dieser sorte. in meinen praktikas na klar mehr und kollegen na klar auch diverse. trotzdem macht mich sowas sauer.

danke an alle meine anderen gäste die mit mir respektvoll und professionell arbeiten und meine arbeit und mein fachwissen zu schätzen wissen.

text:
this saturday! it's never too early to learn about consent! 
though we often associate consent only with sexual assault, the truth is that it is an essential aspect of all relationships. people (even kids) have the right to set boundaries about their bodies, their possessions, and their actions, and we need to respect those boundaries.

in this class, parents (or grandparents, teachers, or anyone who loves kids) will learn how to teach their children about consent, body autonomy, communication, and self-worth.

.
天啊～～小編真的太驚喜了😆
最近迷上韓國網絡劇的小編要來推坑大家囉！
這是一部叫做"좀 예민해도 괜찮아"的網絡劇
中文譯名直翻叫做"有一點敏感也沒關係"
現在出到第二季了喔～
第一季的連結小編也會放在下面有興趣的朋友們可以去看看
包準一看就愛上～～😘
-
第一季講述的是韓國大學生在大學生涯中常遇到的各類議題
在其他網絡劇裡面一般是不會這麼直接的探討一些比較敏感的議題
但這部"有一點敏感也沒關係"卻很勇敢的提出來
並利用這部劇教導現在的年輕世代遇到這類問題可以怎麼應對跟解決
像是前輩和教授的言語性騷擾、女性主義者、大學必修的戀愛學分、#metoo 等等
這些韓國非常熱門的卻也有些敏感的話題
全部都能在第一季裡面看到喔！
真的非常非常棒～～👍👍👍
-
而這次第二季的預告我們可以看到
場景移到了剛邁入社會的新鮮人在職場跟實習會遇到的一些狀況
讓小編已經期待到碗都要敲破了啦😍
2/1（五）下午18:00首播
有興趣的朋友千萬不要錯過！！！
-
播出時間：每週二、五 下午六點整更新
趕快跟著"有一點敏感也沒關係"一起來了解韓國職場到底是什麼樣子吧🤔
-
第一季全季觀看連結：https://youtu.be/jjgnt-bf30a
第二季預告：https://youtu.be/-su_u3n-fu0

our second week of mindfulness monday will focus on using an object for grounding. for this exercise, you can choose any object that you like, but preferably something you can hold onto. turn the object over. consider your senses and describe it to yourself. what colour is it? what does it look like? is it textured? does it have a smell? does it make noise? describe it to yourself in as much detail as you can. 
this technique helps to re-establish a sense of focus and control for individuals who feel overwhelmed. repeat with as many objects as you would like!  #saffroncentre #mindfulnessmonday #ibelieveyou #metoo #timesup
name: SAFFRON Sexual Assault Centre

text:
it's been awhile since i've introduced myself and there are some new faces around here, so hi! my name is sydney, and i've got stories. i like hiking and i have feelings. i am #hikingmyfeelings all over the us to keep my type 2 diabetes in check and to manage my mental health. my adventure buddy for life (@maker_of_waves) and i live in our van full-time and are currently in san diego while we plan my speaking tour. 
my life did a 180 when i was diagnosed with diabetes in late 2017. it wasn't until after i quit my job without a backup plan last year that i realized that my normal coping mechanisms in times of stress - eating and drinking my feelings - were replaced by hiking my feelings. i am incredibly introspective and i wanted to know why i was eating and drinking my feelings to begin with. on the trail in june 2018, the universe stopped me dead in my tracks, tapped me on the shoulder, and reminded me of the rape i survived 12+ years ago. after that, i had instant clarity: i've been thru-hiking life with an invisible backpack full of my trauma (now dubbbed my #traumapack). every time i hit the trail, i unpack this backpack, and connect the dots between trauma and life. and then i write about it.

starting in late march, we are driving around the us while i share the story of how two thru-hikes across catalina island on the #transcatalinatrail helped me heal my mind and body. this ain't your mama's trail review, and i want to be super clear here: i am not a doctor. i am new to the outdoor space. i've always enjoyed being outside in my athletic pursuits, and i am new to all of this.

i didn't pick this, it picked me when the trail saved my life (literally with regards to living with diabetes and mental illness, and also in that omg so fluffy woo woo nature feelings kind of way). i'm not sponsored. my education and work experience is rooted in storytelling on a grand scale and i spent the last decade+ helping big brands (nbc, the wienermobile, snickers and more) share their stories. i know my skills and story can be shared to make this planet a better place, and that's my mission in 2019 and beyond.

that's why i'm here, that's my story. what's yours?

text:
/ perempuan butuh syariat islam, bukan ruu pks /
.
pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan, pratama julia sunjandari, menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.
.
pasalnya, menurut pratma, bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.
.
pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks, “pertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai ‘amanah’ beijing platform for action (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa ‘kontrol seksual’ itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.”
.
kedua, kata pratma julia, merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagi qawwam (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga, menikam syariat islam. kalangan liberal, dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah.
.
“menjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata,” ungkapnya kepada mnews, rabu (30/1/2019).
.
.
——

text: some food for thought - went to superstore the other day to renew my insurance and went looking through the baby stuff that was on sale. for the life of my i couldn’t find a shirt for boys that didn’t have something sexualizing them and basically making them this sort of “ladies man”. i felt uncomfortable putting either of my sons in these clothes labelling them as such, as i don’t want them to grow up thinking it’s okay to be a “ladies man”. i want them to grow up and respect women, not use them and have a bunch of ladies on the side to cycle through at random (this is how i define ladies man). with clothes with labels like these being prevalent for boys from birth, are we surprised that there is a #metoo movement? maybe you might think i’m over reacting, and maybe i am, but i refuse to let my sons be “little romeos” or “ladies men”. stop sexualizing our children and let them be kids and figure out their own identities and learn to respect women! #babyboy #babyclothes #metoo #everydaysexism #respectwomen

text:
six french women and the journalists who published their accounts of sexual harassment are facing a defamation suit by the man they accused. former green party politician and paris city official, denis baupin, prompted a trial refuting the allegations.

in 2016, mediapart website and france inter radio published accounts of 14 women, accusing baupin of sexually harassing them, which included groping and sexting. the women, who were fellow green party members, alleged the acts took place between 1998-2013. baupin resigned from the lower house of parliament when the reports were released in may of 2016. a nine-month judicial investigation was completed with no charges filed.

emmanuel pierrat, baupin’s lawyer, said his client is focused on clearing his name and hoped to prove that website and radio stations were unfair in their coverage.

#rebelkulturemagazine #internationalnews #metoo #paris

text:
"typically when we think of alcoholism, we think of how it’s embodied in men. alcoholism is associated with character traits like a short temper, extreme belligerence, and a lack of respect for other people and their boundaries — traits which are a common part of toxic masculinity. however, alcoholism affects women in ways that aren’t always talked about, both as victims of the out-of-control drinking of others and as subjects of alcoholism in ways that don’t meet the common narrative." read more about 'the weird relationship between women and alcoholism' by elaine reilly only at feministwednesday.com

text:
legality and morality have never alligned.  when they do, we will have no use for a legal system of state sponsored slavery.  natural law will be inherent and will be the only law anyone is obligated to abide by.

many people find the comparison between the jewish holocaust and the animal holocaust offensive.

just because you may be offended, does not mean you're correct or justified in that sentiment.

in order to defend the position that such a comparison cannot be made, you will need to 'name that trait'. name a trait that if present in humans, that if not present in non humans, would give humans a right to exploit non humans to the point of slavery and mass murder.

i couldn't name one.  that's why i went vegan.

text:
it's been awhile since i've introduced myself and there are some new faces around here, so hi!

my name is sydney, and i've got stories. i like hiking and i have feelings. i am #hikingmyfeelings all over the us to keep my type 2 diabetes in check and to manage my mental health. my adventure buddy for life (@maker_of_waves) and i live in our van full-time and are currently in san diego while we plan my speaking tour.

my life did a 180 when i was diagnosed with diabetes in late 2017. it wasn't until after i quit my job without a backup plan last year that i realized that my normal coping mechanisms in times of stress - eating and drinking my feelings - were replaced by @hikingmyfeelings. i am incredibly introspective and i wanted to know why i was eating and drinking my feelings to begin with. on the trail in june 2018, the universe stopped me dead in my tracks, tapped me on the shoulder, and reminded me of the rape i survived 12+ years ago. after that, i had instant clarity: i've been thru-hiking life with an invisible backpack full of my trauma (now dubbbed my #traumapack). every time i hit the trail, i unpack this backpack, and connect the dots between trauma and life. and then i write about it.

starting in late march, we are driving around the us while i share the story of how two thru-hikes across catalina island on the #transcatalinatrail helped me heal my mind and body. this ain't your mama's trail review, and i want to be super clear here: i am not a doctor. i am new to the outdoor space. i've always enjoyed being outside in my athletic pursuits, and i am new to all of this.

i didn't pick this, it picked me when the trail saved my life (literally with regards to living with diabetes and mental illness, and also in that omg so fluffy woo woo nature feelings kind of way). i'm not sponsored. my education and work experience is rooted in storytelling on a grand scale and i spent the last decade+ helping big brands (nbc, the wienermobile, snickers and more) share their stories. i know my skills and story can be shared to make this planet a better place, and that's my mission in 2019 and beyond. that's why i'm here, that's my story. what's yours?

my life did a 180 when i was diagnosed with diabetes in late 2017. it wasn't until after i quit my job without a backup plan last year that i realized that my normal coping mechanisms in times of stress - eating and drinking my feelings - were replaced by  i am incredibly introspective and i wanted to know why i was eating and drinking my feelings to begin with. on the trail in june 2018, the universe stopped me dead in my tracks, tapped me on the shoulder, and reminded me of the rape i survived 12+ years ago. after that, i had instant clarity: i have been thru-hiking life with an invisible backpack full of my trauma (now dubbbed my  every time i hit the trail, i unpack this backpack, and connect the dots between trauma and life. and then i write about it.

staing in late march, we are driving around the us while i share the story of how two thru-hikes across catalina island on the  helped me heal my mind and body. this ain't your mama's trail review, and i want to be super clear here: i am not a doctor. i am new to the outdoor space. i have always enjoyed being outside in my athletic pursuits, and i am new to all of this.

i didn't pick this, it picked me when the trail saved my life (literally with regards to living with diabetes and mental illness, and also in that omg so fluffy woo woo nature feelings kind of way). i am not sponsored. my education and work experience is rooted in storytelling on a grand scale and i spent the last decade+ helping big brands (nbc, the wienermobile, snickers and more) share their stories. i know my skills and story can be shared to make this planet a better place, and that's my mission in 2019 and beyond. that's why i am here, that's my story. what's yours?

love, peace and happiness war das motto der hippie-bewegung, die in den 1960er jahren entstanden ist.
die sexuelle befreiung der frauen hat jedoch mehr als 50 jahre später, so scheint es mir, zu einem verständnis von „ständiger, sexueller verfügbarkeit“ geführt. wie sonst konnte aus der freiheitsliebenden hippie-bewegung eine globale #metoo und #neinheißtnein bewegung werden? und welche rolle spielt dabei das internet?

ich denke jedoch, dass die sehnsucht nach vertrauensvoller intimität geblieben ist. denn gerade in der sexualität kann wahre begegnung und emotionale bindung stattfinden, wenn wir es zulassen und uns so zeigen können, wie wir sind. wie seht ihr das?

text:
when people judge my vulnerability that’s okay. that’s healing they need to do and it’s not my concern what they think. ⁣
⁣
some people get uncomfortable with other’s vulnerability because they aren’t comfortable being vulnerable themselves. usually because of fear, shame, guilt, or the way they were programmed to believe it’s weakness. ⁣
⁣
we should be able to share our stories and messages to the world without judgement. ⁣
⁣
do i personally feel there is a way to share that is beautiful & inspiring over scary and depressing? absolutely. i love hearing stories of redemption and people who find the silver linings in all things.  but at the end of the day if we don’t like what someone is sharing, instead of judging them we could just send love and don’t read or listen to what they share. ⁣
we have a choice. ⁣
for instance, i don’t follow people who are constantly posting negativity, sadness or complaining. ⁣
also i don’t watch the news. ever. ⁣
⁣
for so long our society taught women (still does) to not talk about the taboo things...⁣
sex, abuse, rape, domestic violence, alcohol addiction and hell, really any feelings that go below the surface. we have the opportunity to change that. we can turn our messes into our messages. i know i have. ⁣
⁣
there are ways to share that will inspire others through your strength of overcoming adversities, and the journey you are on for healing. ⁣
⁣
don’t be shy. the world needs your story. your healing and inspiration can help raise the frequency of the planet! ⁣
⁣
#soulup sisters! 💫💞🙌🏻⁣
⁣
⁣
.⁣⁣
.⁣⁣
.⁣⁣

.⁣⁣
.⁣⁣

join us today (monday, feb. 4th at 2 p.m. est), for a discussion on findings from our latest research, the case of the cultural influencers. in recent years, the power of popular entertainment to inspire large audiences and shift cultural norms has become a topic of growing interest in the social advocacy space. as part of our power of pop series, this new research examines three cases of high-profile entertainers and athletes speaking out or advocating for a social and/or policy change. during the webinar, we will discuss key findings from our analysis of colin kaepernick and the take a knee protest, as well as practical recommendations for those seeking to work directly or indirectly with cultural influencers to shift narratives. we will also hear from guest speakers marya bangee, executive director of @iwillharness, and nationally recognized cultural strategist erin potts, who will talk about their work at the intersection of culture,
entertainment and social change.

text:
jojo and i had the blessed opportunity to attend the #saltcompany conference this past weekend. upon walking in and seeing 2,300 college kids praising god, we were immediately humbled. jojo and i were not the ones to go to church or attend anything like this in college. we didn’t know who jesus was; heck we didn’t know who we were. i wouldn’t trade my testimony for anything. i am the follower i am today because of where i have been. yet i can’t help but praise god for what he is doing in this next generation. 
i am grateful for the salt community and the work they are doing. this conference covered tough topics. how do we respond to #metoo? what does racial reconciliation look like? as christians why do we suffer? 
the salt conference made a stance that they would not shy away from tough topics and that they stand on the truth of the gospel-no matter what.

i am humbled to serve alongside these students, pastors, and leaders. 
thank you jesus for all that you have done and all that is yet to be done. 
#saltcompany #saltconference2019 #

text:
you know i’m all about each of us taking control and creating a life we love! well one thing i’m working on this year, and for the rest of my life, is nutrition!
.
sometime in 2018 i had a mourning period. a time when i literally sat down and cried over the fact that i can no longer eat whatever i want, whenever i want and not have it affect me. it’s okay to mourn this!
.
but then it was time to move on! i stared these questions straight in the face and had some heart-to-heart conversations with myself.
.
- jaren and i have awesome plans for our future! how can i make sure i do everything possible to keep my body healthy enough to do these things?
.
- what does eating to maintain my weight actually look like? all i know is what eating to lose weight looks like and vice-versa, eating whatever i want looks like. and how do i figure this out? (if you’re wondering the same thing, listen to @biceps.after.babies podcast on reverse dieting).
.
- how can i be patient with myself as i re-train my brain to let go of things like huge sunday desserts, entire boxes of candy during movies and airplane rides and other things that have become staples?
.
as the year has started and i’ve begun my lifestyle change i have had to remind myself that i’m not changing these actions for a short time to lose weight but because these actions no longer align with the lifelong goals i’ve set for myself.
.
so here’s to a entering a new phase of life. the one where i #ditchthediet  mentality and start creating an every day diet that aligns with my goals!
.
açaí breakfast bowl
.
1 packet original açaí blend
1 medium banana (100g) frozen
1/4 cup almond milk
50 grams raspberries 
50 grams blueberries
1 serving granola
.
mix açaí packet, banana & almond milk in blender. top with berries and granola.
.
serves 1
393 calories. c:69 f:11 p:6
#asoulsurvivorbreakfast

text:
as we enter black history month, i thought i would quote the fotmer first lady herself, michelle obama.

courage can be a hard thing to find when you have experienced abuse, marginalization, and aggression for who you are or who you love. that is one of the things that i think is so amazing about the growth of social movements like black lives matters and #metoo. when we find others, who have a shared pain, that pain can turn into a fire that fuels us and social change. 
the same principle holds for support and recovery groups. having others who have had some similar experiences can help each of us to find the courage needed to speak our truth. even exposure to these movements can help spread courage, whether it is speaking up at a rally, sharing with a partner, or seeking out therapy to work through what has happened.

and on the other side of things is that piece about hope. when you live with depression, anxiety and ptsd it can be very hard to find hope for yourself and your future. that is why one of the important aspects of my work as a therapist is to be a holder of hope. i hold hope for the future that my clients cannot yet see for themselves. part of the reasons that i am able to hold this hope is that i have seen powerful transformation and change happen. i have seen people be able to reclaim their lives and find new purpose. i am passionate about helping others let go of the pain of their past, live more fully in the present and develop hope for the future. if that sounds right for you, check out the link in my bio for more info on me and my practice. #transaffirm #traumatherapysd #hope #courage

text:
"you're trying to steal my man..."
we heard a mother say this to her daughter in a video when the daughter was trying to tell her mother that her boyfriend had been molesting her. of course we were sick to our stomachs and livid at the same time. how could any parent say this?! let us be clear, if you are a child and this statement has been made to you, it is a lie! a child is never responsible for the behavior of an adult. a child can never steal a man or a woman from an adult because normal, well-adjusted, and mentally stable adults are not attracted to or interested in sex with children!!! if anyone thinks a child is trying to or is capable of "stealing their partner", that means there is something wrong with the adult making this statement as well as the adult who is abusing the child. and, if you're a parent or adult who has made this statement to or about a child, you need to check yourself and ask yourself why you value a relationship with a child molester and sexual deviant over the safety and wellbeing of your child? we also need everyone to understand that this type of messaging is what keeps kids from disclosing abuse in their homes and in their families. so, even if you're not the parent of a child making this completely asinine statement, but you've said it about someone else's child, you're contributing to the problem and you're part of the reason why so many kids are suffering in silence. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist  #superbowl

text:
🔞 с*ксуальная революция провалилась?
⠀
популярное движение конца 60х приравнивало кексуальную свободу к свободе личности. молодёжь отрицала закостенелые ценности родителей. они выступали против запрета кекса до брака и за увеличение числа партнёров. кекс стал выноситься из-за закрытых дверей спален.
⠀
кекс стал рекламироваться как главнейший показатель успешности. сожительство без обязательств, друзья по кексу - молодёжь выступала против брака. они видели, что у родителей не получалось быть счастливыми, и винили в этом штампы и условности.
⠀
что же творилось на самом деле?
⠀
⚠️женщины при таких "свободных отношениях" свободны не стали. социологини университета невады выяснили, что в семьях с зарегистрированным консервативным браком и в семьях со "свободными отношениями" всё так же работа по дому и обслуживанию была взвалена на женщин. при этом у мужчин, сожительствующих без брака, обязанностей было меньше. женщины в "свободных отношениях" выполняли ту же работу, но без какой-либо правовой и экономической охраны.
⠀
ещё один из худших плодов кексуальной революции: закрепление двойных стандартов. мужчина стал считаться успешным, если пропустил через свою кровать сотни женщин. женщина так и осталась либо святой, либо распутницей. мужчине можно, женщина - шлюпка. мужчина - плейбой, женщина - подстилка.
⠀
⛔кексуальная революция предоставила доступ к женским телам, при этом самих женщин обозвав последними словами. кексуального освобождения не произошло. при этом порno, чьё влияние возрасло в тысячи раз, говорит нам: без кекса ты неудачник(-ца), женщина должна и так и эдак и вот так ещё.
⠀
🚫и женщины загнаны меж двух углов: стать продвинутой шлюпкой, или отсталой монашкой. так себе выбор.
⠀
мы думали, что будем свободны. а по итогу оказалось, что теперь мы должны мужчинам кекс в свободной форме без обязательств, ведь "ты же не меркантильная". но на нас так же продолжает падает клеймо шлюпки. и по прежнему никто никому ничего не должен. только:
⠀
☑️будь красивой,
☑️будь доступной,
☑️будь весёлой,
☑️раскрепощённой,
☑️умей в кекс,
☑️но ни о чём не проси, ведь я тебе ничего не должен.
⠀
❓как думаете, я сгущаю краски и кексуальная революция всё же больше помогла?
name: Феминизм с человеческим лицом

⠀ ⚠️женщины при таких `` свободных отношениях '' свободны не стали . социологини университета невады выяснили , что в семьях с зарегистрированным консервативным браком и в семьях со `` свободными отношениями '' всё так же работа по дому и обслуживанию была взвалена на женщин . при этом у мужчин , сожительствующих без брака , обязанностей было меньше . женщины в `` свободных отношениях '' выполняли ту же работу , но без какой-либо правовой и экономической охраны . ⠀ ещё один из худших плодов кексуальной революции : закрепление двойных стандартов . мужчина стал считаться успешным , если пропустил через свою кровать сотни женщин . женщина так и осталась либо святой , либо распутницей . мужчине можно , женщина - шлюпка . мужчина - плейбой , женщина - подстилка . ⠀ ⛔кексуальная революция предоставила доступ к женским телам , при этом самих женщин обозвав последними словами . кексуального освобождения не произошло . при этом порno , чьё влияние возрасло в тысячи раз , говорит нам : без кекса ты неудачник ( -ца ) , женщина должна и так и эдак и вот так ещё . ⠀ 🚫и женщины загнаны меж двух углов : стать продвинутой шлюпкой , или отсталой монашкой . так себе выбор . ⠀ мы думали , что будем свободны . а по итогу оказалось , что теперь мы должны мужчинам кекс в свободной форме без обязательств , ведь `` ты же не меркантильная '' . но на нас так же продолжает падает клеймо шлюпки . и по прежнему никто никому ничего не должен . только : ⠀ ☑️будь красивой , ☑️будь доступной , ☑️будь весёлой , ☑️раскрепощённой , ☑️умей в кекс , ☑️но ни о чём не проси , ведь я тебе ничего не должен . ⠀ ❓как думаете , я сгущаю краски и кексуальная революция всё же больше помогла ?

text:
the #metoo movement has certainly arrived in #india, causing a media buzz and creating a greater public discussion about gender-based #violence, validating #feminist campaigns and discourse. though #young indian women have notably led #metoo and made great strides in calling out #sexism in their society, young #dalit #women’s voices have not been prominent among them.

निश्चित तौर पर #metoo भारत देश मे भी आया है। जिसे मीडिया ने इतनी नजर बख्शी है की लिंग आधारित हिंसा के बारे में अधिक से अधिक सार्वजनिक चर्चा पैदा हुई है, जो नारीवादी अभियानों की अहमियत को मान्यता देता हुआ मालूम होता है। मगर उन युवा भारतीय महिलाओं का उल्लेखनीय नेतृत्व प्रंशसनिया है जिन्होंने अपने समाज की औरतों के प्रति हो रहे उत्पीड़न के खिलाफ आवाज उठाई हैं, युवा दलित महिलाओं की आवाज़ उनमें प्रमुख नहीं है। frida and @the.fbomb fellow, amna nasir, writes about dalit women fight, in her #spotlight story: https://buff.ly/2rfyk8n (हिंदी अनुवाद भी उपलब्ध) link in bio!

text:
i meet so many women who tell me they were in school or college with me. especially in my sobo sojourns  since i grew up there. and especially at my public appearances or performances  what i find most interesting is when these women emphasise on the fact that they were junior 😊 way way juniour you see they specify!! as if being younger is a qualification or achievement of some sort  and automatically makes u better or more worthy ... patriarchy is so so entrenched in the human psyche in ways many of us dont even recognise 😊

#patriarchy #freedom #metoo #women #respect #loveurself

text:
👩🏿‍🦱 voz // bia ferreira é cantora, compositora, ativista e faz uso de sua música para educar, conscientizar a respeito das demandas de luta do movimento anti-racismo no brasil. em turnê pela europa, bia lotou uma sala em lisboa, segundo relato do jornalista pedro reis: "não conhecia a música da bia ferreira. descobri ontem, depois de ler um artigo no público. por acaso, no dia em que ela tinha concerto em lisboa. consegui bilhetes dois minutos antes de esgotar. a @soubiaferreira ainda não tem nenhum álbum gravado e, segundo a própria, foi a primeira pessoa da família a sair do brasil. no seu primeiro show na europa, esgotou uma sala em lisboa com mais de 400 pessoas e deixou toda a gente rendida. acho que vamos ouvir falar muito dela no futuro". .
.
💬 no artigo do jornal público mencionado pelo pedro, bia define seu estilo: "não é soul, r&b, rap nem reggae. é tudo isso, 'é mmp – música de mulher preta'". para ouvir hoje.

text:
first episode of season 2 is out now! 🎉 this week i sit down to have a conversation with founder/ceo of @98society which is a women owned business and brand that focuses on sexual assault survivor services, stories, and apparel! we start breaking down the stigmas around sexual assault and dive deep into how we as a society can really start to move towards a zero tolerance culture. this conversation is so important in light of recent movements like #metoo and #timesup and is really relevant as we are still seeing people in the media at fault for sexual abuse. click the link in my bio to hear or watch the full interview!! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

first episode of season 2 is out now! 🎉 this week i sit down to have a conversation with founder/ceo of @98society which is a women owned business and brand that focuses on sexual assault survivor services, stories, and apparel! we start breaking down the stigmas around sexual assault and dive deep into how we as a society can really start to move towards a zero tolerance culture. this conversation is so important in light of recent movements like #metoo and #timesup and is really relevant as we are still seeing people in the media at fault for sexual abuse. click the link in my bio to hear or watch the full interview!! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
20% of females aged between 16-59 have experienced a form of sexual assault. 80% of sexual offences go unreported. 
this week is the uk’s sexual abuse and sexual violence awareness week. it’s a week that we shouldn’t need to bring awareness to in society, because it shouldn’t be an issue. everyone deserves to feel safe, respected and in control of their own body. speak out and you will be heard #itsnotok

text:
с 26 января по 3 февраля 2019 в городе старый оскол на базе дворца спорта «аркада» прошло первенство 🇷🇺 россии по тяжелой атлетике. 
в соревнованиях приняли участие юноши и девушки в возрасте 13-17 лет. 💪🏻
⠀
спортсмены сшор по тяжелой атлетике «мгфсо» москомспорта завоевали 4 медали турнира. 🏅
⠀
среди девушек до 15 лет в весовой категории до 71 кг победу одержала светлана прокопенко, по результатам двоеборья набрав 165 кг. среди юношей в весовой категории до 73 кг бронзу завоевал семен ворона (двоеборье, 200 кг). 🔥
⠀
среди спортсменок до 17 лет серебряным призером в весовой категории до 45 кг стала алина гузикова (двоеборье, 118 кг), бронзовую награду в весовой категории до 59 кг завоевала виктория соколова (двоеборье, 138 кг).🙏🏻 ⠀
#команда_мгфсо #team_mgfso #москва #мгфсо #тяжелаяатлетика #первенствороссии #спорт #старыйоскол #mgfso #москомспорт #moscow #moskomsport #sport #like4like #follow #followme #asmr #fortnite #btsarmy #metoo #timesup #marchforourlives
name: ГБУ "МГФСО" Москомспорта

text:
***black history month highlight*** february 4th - tarana burke, founder of the #metoo movement. tarana burke is a civil rights activist who was the original founder of the "me too" movement, which she started in 2006. it later became a global phenomenon that raised awareness about sexual harassment, abuse, and assault in society in 2017. 
tarana burke was born september 12, 1973 in the bronx, ny. in 2017 burke and other influential female activists were named "the silence breakers" by time magazine. she currently serves at the girls for gender equity in brooklyn as its senior director. #blackhistoryisamericanhistory #excellence #blackhistorymonth #upcwestorange #upcwo #blackfemaleleadership

text:
consent is a critical concept for reducing sexual violence, and for reducing sexual exploitation of all kinds. a key component of our prevention programs is geared entirely towards teaching kids about their rights to body privacy and integrity (what makes for "good touch" or "bad touch")--and what to do if they are violated. though we may feel squeamish about talking about these things with children, it's important to start talking about them early and often, for their own protection.
#prevention #education #raisingawareness #metoo #endsexualviolence #endexploitation #endrapeculture

text:
nuevo artículo en @topotabernario 
sobre consentimiento, educación misógina y relaciones de poder. “la cultura misógina da por sentada la debilidad del «no» femenino: «preguntar e insistir funciona». nos lo dice el estereotipo de la mujer que se hace de rogar, nos lo enseña el coach del cortejo que dice que «la mujer no sabe lo que quiere, tú debes mostrárselo». el hombre educado en valores patriarcales lo tiene claro: la mujer dice que no porque no quiere ser considerada una facilona. la negativa es para la masculinidad hegemónica un reto de una mujer que se hace la dura en lugar de ser una barrera que tenemos que respetar.” link en bio

#feminismo #masculinidades #gender #machismo #igualdad #masculino #noesno #metoo #masculinity #instagram #instapic #instagood #writing #picoftheday

😏🔥 y’know that frustrating cliche that “men love bitches” and “women love assholes”? it’s not totally untrue. because y’know what bitch-assholes have in common? big, fat, strong boundaries. boundaries to a fault. and while i’m not encouraging you to go full bitch-asshole, like...15% wouldn’t kill you. ⠀
::⠀
having good boundaries means you know what you need to feel good, safe and okay (with yourself and with others), and you are comfortable ensuring those needs get met. even if it means ruffling feathers or someone being disappointed/momentarily pissed at you. even if it means risking a new relationship because you have to have a hard ‘n honest conversation about what he thinks of the #metoo movement. even if it means sucking it up and going home when you reeeally wanna stay over, bone, and take a shower together next-day after knowing the guy for like 4 hours.⠀
::⠀
yes — good boundaries means that sometimes you don’t even get to do what you want to do, because you understand that your cumulative needs are bigger than your impulsive wants. i repeat: healthy boundaries dictate that your needs take priority over your wants. because boundaries are evvverything — it’s how we teach people to understand, respect, and love us, and casual shower sex unfortunately might not fit into that blueprint (or totes might - i don’t know your life!).🤷🏻‍♀️ ⠀
::⠀
people who get this and consistently ace their boundaries are more attractive to just about everybody, because they aren’t being people-please-y backward-benders who betray themselves for likes and approval. they’re okay if they fall outta someone’s good graces, but remain in solid standing with themselves. they walk through the world having their own back first, oozing self-respect, and yeah — we can smell it on them. it smells delicious. like bacon and tom ford, y’all. real good.
::
you deserve to smell yummy to both yourself and others. to know that your boundaries are important enough to be honored. first by you, and then by anyone else who cares enough to have your back and love you accordingly. but if you’re not modeling that 1st? uh...why should/would anyone else? (for real though.) good talk. 🙌🏻

text:
just a thought on #intersectionality as an ideal vs the reality on the ground. even with the rise of movements like #metoo, #timesup, #totalshutdown and #blacklivesmatter, we've seen that there is still a gap in the 'whos stories' get told and whose lens they are told through. in addressing issues from a broad spectrum as opposed to a nuanced and intersectional perspective, many people's experiences fall through the cracks. 
closer to home, we still fail to create mainstream spaces and narratives that address the lived experiences of the #transgendercommunity for instance as though they don't exist, many people here are still of the opinion that being #transgender is an american thing as though this is some trend or exported cultural fed. the lives and identities of people who occupy multiple identities are often erased in the pursuit of what we think is a just world. not everyone's story and lived experience is prioritised. 
in cases where we know we can't represent everyone's story ourselves, we have a responsibility to create and share spaces with the marginalised so they can represent themselves in a way that best represents their lived reality. everyone's story deserves to be heard because visibility is important. and there is nothing more powerful than empowering people with the ability to self-represent. 
#intersectionalfeminism #intersectionality #lgbtqi #womensbodies #womensrights #southafricanblogger #activism #mondaymotivation #wokeproject

text:
meet our founder!!!
tyde-courtney edwards is the founding director of ballet after dark. she's also a classically trained ballerina, choreographer, art model and survivor of sexual assault. born and raised in baltimore city, she is a graduate of the baltimore school for the arts and has over 20 years of dance training and experience. trained in various styles of dance including classical and contemporary ballet, pointe, modern, lyrical, jazz, tap and hip-hop, she conceptualized ballet after dark after struggling with recovery following her sexual assault. tyde-courtney has trained with debbie allen dance academy, dance theatre of harlem, peabody conservatory, joffrey ballet, alvin ailey and other institutions while receiving training from local dance pioneers such as anton wilson, norma pera and stephanie powell. she currently resides in baltimore city.

we're healing at ballet after dark, llc... where every girl is a ballerina!👑 be sure to visit the website today at www.balletafterdark.com! become a member and take advantage of new home workout and ballet tutorials being uploaded!

text:
"les réalisatrices seront représentées à un niveau inédit au sein de la compétition : 7 des 17 films en compétition, soit 41 % des œuvres, ont été réalisés par des femmes. avec respectivement 14 % et 5 % en 2018, cannes et venise font pâle figure." @lemondefr « les débats de l’année dernière nous ont ouvert les yeux et quand les yeux sont ouverts, vous prenez des décisions différentes », explique à l’afp m. kosslick à propos des mouvements #metoo contre le harcèlement sexuel et @timesupnow visant la discrimination sexuelle dans le secteur du divertissement. mais, assure le directeur, « on ne l’aurait pas fait si les films avaient été mauvais ». l’ours d’or a d’ailleurs été décerné ces deux dernières années à des femmes, la roumaine adina pintilie (touch me not) et la hongroise ildiko enyedi (on body and soul). .
.
.

pour la responsable du groupe « @womenandhollywood», #melissasilverstein @melsil cette importante part de réalisatrices tombe d’autant mieux qu’aucune femme ne figure parmi les nominés aux oscars du meilleur film ou réalisateur. dans ce contexte, les festivals sont, selon elle, essentiels pour assurer la diversité du secteur : un festival « permet de se faire remarquer, qu’on en parle dans les journaux du monde entier. les gens verront votre film et les acheteurs et autres programmateurs le verront ». sera ainsi signé durant la berlinale un engagement de parité, non contraignant, que cannes, venise et d’autres grands festivals ont déjà paraphé.

la danoise lone scherfig ouvrira la compétition avec la première mondiale de the kindness of strangers, un drame qui se déroule à new york. la française agnès varda, 90 ans, présentera un nouveau documentaire autobiographique hors compétition. les superstars indiennes ranveer singh et alia bhatt fouleront le tapis rouge pour la première de gully boy de zoya akhtar, une des rares réalisatrices à gros budget à bollywood.

@berlinale - #berlinale international film festival @5050x2020 @5050by2020

text:
it's a long shot but does anyone know who these two barnyard animals are? i get on the train and i am stood nearby, one on right takes a selfie and i accidentally glance and find it's mostly me. 30 seconds later i see i have been circled on said image and i am about to be posted on something. i asked (polite-ish) 'do you mind being a little more subtle with what you're about to post?' to which the beast to the right said no. .
i didn't reply, nor do i mind going on social media, i would just love to know what the joke was. can't quite work out what's funny about a short fat man in a green tie, but then my attempts at stand up were quite poor so it's a joke i didn't quite get. i was less discrete about my pic, though she kept turning her head and i had to get off next stop. got the mate (who in fairness didn't take the pic, but was party to whatever the joke was!)
.

text:
loving lessons:loving your body💛. i’ve always felt a separation between mind and body in similar way that people tend to separate physical beauty from “personality”. with that, i had i vague likeness for my personality, but close to zero for my body. ..
like most women, i was taught to see what was wrong with my body instead of what was right. thus, i was not good to it. specifically: i didn’t eat mindfully. i never stayed consistently active. worst of all, i spoke negatively about it. i was not taught how take care of it. i was not taught that it was even something of importance. basic safety and anatomy, yes. but true care and support in terms of one’s body was not present. this isn’t meant to blame my parents. i understand. you don’t know what you don’t know. ..
now i believe that my physical and mental beauty feel brightest when they’re working together. to best appreciate my body, i have to make the conscious decision to care for it with action and words of gratitude. ..
their journey (my mind and body) is lifelong. but, their relationship is finally reciprocal. i feel genuine love for my body and mind for all they are and everything they give to me.
..
to my body, i will protect you. i will take care of you. i will seek out partners who will love you the way i do. .
.
.

text:
perempuan butuh syariat islam, bukan ruu pks
.
pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan, pratama julia sunjandari, menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.

pasalnya, menurut pratma, bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya. atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.

pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks, “pertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai ‘amanah’ beijing platform for action (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa ‘kontrol seksual’ itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.” kedua, kata pratma julia, merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagi qawwam (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga, menikam syariat islam. kalangan liberal, dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah. “menjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata,” ungkapnya kepada mnews, rabu (30/1/2019). pratma kemudian menjelaskan bahwa umat islam harus berupaya menegakkan syariat islam kaffah sebagai solusi persoalan kekerasan terhadap perempuan, “tidak kalah penting mengedukasi umat bahwa persoalan kekerasan seksual, bahkan pelecehan kehormatan perempuan tak akan terjadi jika khilafah tegak. syariat kaffah itu memiliki hukum yang amat memuliakan manusia apalagi perempuan dengan hukum-hukum sistem pergaulannya,” tukasnya.[]

text:
this week is sexual violence awareness week. if you are a survivor, we believe & support you. 💛
we often hear cases of why survivors don’t report their assault to the police. 
there are a myriad of factors why someone doesn’t report. this doesn’t make their experience or trauma any less valid.
•
today we wanted to share someone’s experience of what happened when they did report their rape to the police. •
swipe right (tw: rape/assault/court)
•
head to the link in our bio to read the full article on @fumble.uk - “i took my rapist to court. this is what happened”.
•
if you are feeling in any way overwhelmed and are in need of support please reach out to:
•
rape crisis helpline: 0808 802 9999
nspcc helpline: 0808 800 5000 
the survivors trust helpline: 0808 801 0818
national domestic violence helpline (24hrs): 0808 2000 247
•
if you wanted to find other services in your area head to our directory - www.standtall.org/organisations
•
image credit: @soydivison ✊🏻✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

text:
and she is off….
_
i can feel myself twitching…
_
im unsettled…
_
i want to go… want to run…
_
that’s what i used to do when i felt vulnerable.
_
instead of facing what it was i was afraid of…
_
usually a feeling… i wasn’t prepared to admit, or a hurt too ashamed to discuss.
_
that need to escape still creeps over my body and it always feels much easier to do that…
_
just disappear …. run away.
_
but is it?
_
the truth is, no…. because you cant run from yourself…
_
and this is how we get lost.
_
we change the external factors…
_
our body…
our hair…
our style…
our scenery…
_
but what we fail to do sometimes…
_
is actually ask ourselves what we are trying to run away from.
_
what are we not facing?
_
what are we not being honest about?
_
what is actually going on right now?
_
what do we want?
_
so, i am staying put … because i know what i am trying to run away from…
_
and that’s hurt… i wasnt quite expecting it, so its caught me off guard.
_
the truth is im scared… i have had a lot of big changes lately, doing a lot of work learning who i am again.
_
so its ok to feel a little scared….because i know, im exactly where i need to be.
_
and that’s right here, in this moment being honest about how i feel and what i want x

text:
offenes frauen*streik vernetzungstreffen

jeden sonntag|16h|frauenmuseum bonn|im krausfeld 10|53111 bonn

am 8.märz findet in bonn ein bundesweit koordinierter frauen*streik statt.
am 9.märz findet in düsseldorf die landesweite großdemo statt.
bis dahin treffen sich alle frauen*, egal ob organisiert oder einzelperson jeden sonntag um 16h im frauenmuseum bonn.
wenn du lust hast, dich mit gleichgesinnten frauen* zu vernetzen und/oder bei der vorbereitung des frauen*streiks mitzuhelfen, komm vorbei!

text:
in 2013, journalist @gingereatspho was trolled online. she received scores of hateful tweets, including a death threat, and a picture of her heavily pregnant (alongside her husband and two-and-half year old daughter) appeared on a fascist website. once the terror subsided, she found herself curious. who were these trolls? and how does one fight back?

over the next five years, gorman spoke to psychologists, trolling victims, law enforcement, academics and, most importantly, the trolls themselves. by infiltrating their online communities and psyches, she made some truly shocking new discoveries.

an intense and compelling read, troll hunting is an important window into the mindset and motivation behind this modern scourge.

troll hunting by ginger gorman is out on thursday. pre-order your copy via the link in our bio

text:
друзья, учитывая участившиеся случаи странных комментариев и личных сообщений содержания типа: «темная сторона йоги. oliko yoga - секта и т.п.» я решила написать данный пост, чтобы ответить сразу всем кто переслал мне данные сообщения, и тем, кто, возможно, просто недоумевает “wtf”.
⠀

я не любитель публично высказываться о своей личной жизни, но тут придется.
⠀

человек, которого зовут александр александрович аброскин 1980 г.р. (мой уже как 6 лет бывший муж) под разными никнэймами и в разных социальных сетях рассылает не имеющую отношения к действительности информацию, касающуюся меня и моей семьи, которая, по его мнению должна
🔴 во-первых, меня запугать и лишить сна;
🔴 во-вторых, отвратить от меня тех, кто уже или потенциально контактирует со мной в контексте моего профессионального занятия - йоги. ⠀

прежде всего я хотела бы сказать, что мне нечего бояться и нечего скрывать, и я не боюсь страшного разоблачения во всех немыслимых грехах.
⠀

согласно мнения эксперта, человек вероятно имеет серьёзные психические нарушения и может быть опасен для себя и окружающих. ⠀

работа по прекращению этого безумия ведётся.
⠀

благодарю тех, кто поддерживает меня в этой ситуации. для меня это очень важно.
⠀

в карусели фото александра и его угрозы.
⠀ ⚠️ если вы хотите мне помочь, блокировать пользователя не достаточно, необходимо пожаловаться на профиль администрации соц. сети на нарушение правил сообщества. ещё будет здорово, если вы пришлёте мне скриншоты его сообщений для использования в деле.

2018 oli elämäni paskin vuosi. olin jo kärsinyt useamman vuoden masennuksesta ja ahdistuksesta jotka olivat huipussaan juuri sinä vuonna. 😞 ei mennyt viikkoakaan ilman paniikkikohtausta, olin lukittautunut kotiin. en pystynyt käymään missään yksin ja ihmissuhteet kärsivät. 2018 mun synttäreillä laivalla jouduin raiskausyrityksen kohteeksi. tämä rikkoi vielä lisää vaikka sain estettyä mitään pahempaa tapahtumasta.  tästä en ole ennen puhunut kuin harvoille, koska koin että se on hävettävä asia. 😪 lukittauduin tämän myötä vielä lisää kotiin. olin melkein ilman ystäviä koko kesän, ylikäytin rauhottavia. jos olin juomassa vedin aina överiksi. en voinut hyvin. alkusyksystä pääsin psykiatriselle ja siitä alkoi ylämäki. muutaman käynnin jälkeen voin jo vähän paremmin ja jotkut asiat hoituivat itsenäisemmin. aloin pitämään huolta itsestäni, sain painoa pois. alotin pajan joka on ollut mulle niin tärkeä paikka! ❤️ ette voi käsittää miten pajalla olo sai mut omaksi itsekseni. mä voin tällä hetkellä paremmin kuin 6 vuoteen. ei enää lähes yhtään ahdistusta, paniikkikohtauksia. mulla on paljon uusi kavereita ❤️ masennuksesta ei jälkeäkään. päästiin lapsettomuushoitoihinkin tänä vuonna ja sekin vielä helpottaa. ❤️👶🏻 3v lapsettomuutta takana on myös ison osan aiemmin mainituista asioista aiheuttanut. jokatapauksessa... mä olen vihdoin siinä vaiheessa elämää että koen olevani puhtaasti oma onnellinen itseni. ❤️ mä selvisin kaikesta tosta. mä olen niin ylpeä itsestäni ja nyt voin vihdoin alkaa rakentamaan mun elämää vakaalle pohjalle! mä selvisin❤️ kiitos jos luit ✨

text:
#metoo on the football field: female empowerment key topic in super bowl ads
#
super bowl ads this year aim increasingly at women, with more messages of female empowerment, as marketers seek to navigate a polarized political environment for the biggest u.s. sporting event. with women making up a large segment of the viewing audience, advertisers are giving them a greater voice and offering messages about women controlling their own destiny, according to previews released ahead of sunday's super bowl liii between the los angeles rams and new england patriots. "we saw advertisers run messages that skew toward women, but they are very careful not to offend men along the way," said timothy calkins, a northwestern university marketing professor who researches super bowl advertising. calkins said, however, that racy sexual ads are unlikely in the #metoo era that has put a spotlight on harassment of women. "i think advertisers are very afraid to run anything remotely suggestive," he said. one of the female empowerment ads features tennis star serena williams for the online dating site bumble, where she speaks about how women can "make the first move" and take control of their lives. "sex and the city" star sarah jessica parker appears in one message where she shocks restaurant staff by ordering stella artois…

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitba – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robe mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state depament and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
в чем разница между сывороточным протеином и мультипротеином? как их сочетать? 
сывороточные изоляты energy pro (для мужчин и для женщин) это монокомпонентые протеины, которые очень быстро повышают уровень аминокислот в крови, так как быстро усваиваются. мультипротеин действует дольше: правильнее назвать его комплексным, поскольку он содержит белки с разной скоростью усвоения.

поэтому сывороточные изоляты energy pro рекомендуется принимать непосредственно перед тренировкой и сразу после нее, а также утром после пробуждения. мультипротеин рекомендуется принимать через пару часов после тренировки и перед сном.
name: Nl - бизнес и здоровье

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
raise your hand if you’ve been marie kondo-ing the heck out of your life? 🙋🏾‍♀️🙋🏽‍♀️🙋🏼‍♀️
_
the simple question that her process poses is..does this spark joy? 💥
_
if not, thank it for what it helped provide you and move on. 
_
to evolve you must eliminate. in order to make space for abundance you have to be willing to let go of what no longer serves you. in order to walk through the double doors, you must close a door. 
_
so tell me, what are you eliminating this week?
.
.
.
.
.

honestly, in my day to day i try my best to hide my light. i become a closet empath. does anyone else do this? i don't exactly know why but it's probably a combination of the fact that my love is overwhelming even for me and i'm scared if i am fully myself some people can not handle me in their lives. i am different. i am so different. so...i smile, i listen, i do, i try and be average, i heal (never to my greatest capacity). today i met a special person. she has a great purpose in life and she doesn't even understand it. she is a survivor. she doesn't even know how much i could feel her and relate to her. she didn't know she is going to change my life as much as i am going to change hers. one day i will be brave enough, until then i am thankful there are others like me who can understand how i feel.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn
